                        modelFields="[text]"
                        name="Text Container Text"
                        text="&lt;p>&lt;em>Once a molecule has been identified as having potential to help people, Duignan tests how it gets processed within the body.&lt;/em>&lt;/p>&lt;p>“The field of pharmacokinetics is all about understanding what the body will do to a medicine once it is taken, because it doesn’t stay there forever, your body eventually eliminates it. To help move that part of the discovery process along, I’ll design experiments to better understand to what degree the medicine is absorbed, metabolized and eliminated and to figure out which molecules might work best for our program. Then, if a molecule or chemical series looks promising, we will also need to conduct experiments to understand what potential molecular interaction risks might exist in patients that will be taking other medications. If there are risks, we will then work to mitigate these risks.&lt;/p>&lt;p>Right now in immunology, we are working on some relatively novel and non-traditional approaches which makes the work even more exciting. I also really like how our teams work closely together. A lot of informal conversations happen during the day and a lot of decisions can be made outside of meetings. The result is our work can be very fast-paced.”&lt;/p>"/>
                </block_15>
